		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nunq[uam] nimis, quod nunq[uam] satis.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Whatever is not enough is never too much.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Inuictus est, qui quatuor virtutibus amictus
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( est.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Unconquerable is he who is clothed in the four virtues.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Fortuna sedens Apellis: nunq[uam] enim stetit.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Apelles"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The fortune of Apelles is seated, and indeed it never stands.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Bona Ethica, et Oeconomica faciunt bonam
						Politicam. Cum Socratis aureo ingenio.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Socrates"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Good ethics and economics make good politics. Together with the golden genius of Socrates.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Virtus currens Apellis: nunq[uam] enim sedit: stet raro.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Apelles"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The virtue of Apelles is running, and indeed it never sits. Rarely will it stand up.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Scopus Ciceronis ex professo:
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Cicero"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="EL">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						πάντων κρα -
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						κράτιστος.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vt Caesaris,
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="EL">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						τὸ πρωτέυειν.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The declared goal of Cicero, to be the best of all men.
				Just as the goal of Cicero is to be the first among all men.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nemo vnq[uam] satis prudens, aut fortis fuit: aut quod tertium est, satis dulcis:
						quem nihil perturbaret, aut offenderet, quicquid accideret turbarum. [T]am industria, 
						effectus est prudentia[e], et fortitudinis:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						nec vllum noui satis industrium.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				No one was every prudent or strong enough (or sweet enough which is the third option),
				whom nothing would have bothered or offended if some turmoil had occurred. 
				Such industria is the effect of prudence and strength; I know that no industry is sufficient enough.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian" marginalia_id="Ha2.091v_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.092r_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.092r.xml" book_id="FolgersHa2">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Gulielmi Birdi dictum de Axiophilo. Illum hominem nunq[uam] vidi iratum; nunq[uam] [A4[r]: tristem; nunq[uam] timidum; nunq[uam] irresolutum; nunq[uam] ignavum, aut languidum; nunq[uam]
						sui, aut aliorum immemorem; nunq[uam] perturbatum vllo Casu. Non noui hominem, beneficioru[m] magis memorem; aut iniuriarum magis
						immemore[m]. Nec scio alique[m], cuius
						rationes, et actiones it&agrave; dependent
						&agrave; Seipso. Ha[e]c ille sobrius generosus 
						de Axiophilo ingenu&egrave;.]
						<!-- Continues onto facing page, left margin, Ha2.092r -->
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="William Bird"/>
					<person name="Axiophilus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The saying of William Bird regarding Axiophilus. I never saw that man angry, never [A4[r]: sad, never timid, never irresolute, never lazy or languid, never forgetful of himself or of others, 
				never disturbed by any happening. I have never known a man more mindful of favors, or
				more forgetful of injuries. Nor do I know of anyone whose reasons and actions depend so much
				on himself. The sensible noble, man naturally finds these things in Axiophilus.]
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
